{
  "text": "The methylation status of the RNA-binding domain of RNABP is believed to regulate splicing pattern on mRNA transcript [CITATION_1] . Methylcytosine binding protein-2 (MeCP2) recognizes 5-methylcytosine on DNA and is a critical transcription factor implicated in neuro-developmental disorders, including Rett syndrome and autism spectrum disorder [CITATION_2] . Y-box-binding protein 1 (YBP1) is a RNA binding protein, which interacts with MeCP2, and this conjugation critically regulates splicing, such that mutations in YBP1 or MeCP2, or alterations in MeCP2 levels (as observed in Rett syndrome), can affect mRNA splicing patterns, and cause aberrant gene expression [CITATION_3] . Thus RNABP methylation status is an important regulator of alternative splicing phenomena.",
